    </div>
    <div class="container cs-section">
        <h3>Define</h3>
        <p>From my observations, I defined 3 key user story statements to synthesize my research insights and findings to summarize how I would be empathizing with Psystem’s users for the webpage updates.</p>
        <h4>Key Research Insights</h4>
        <p>The key research insights I gathered from the user interviews include the following:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>2 of 5 participants expressed interest in learning more about a specific service on a dedicated page aside from the main services page to not feel confused by a lot of information on one webpage.</li>
            <li>All of the participants noted the lack of cohesive appearance for the font family, font weight, and font sizes that distracted them and questioned their trust in the content at different points on a webpage.</li>
            <li>3 of 5 participants noted the navigation menus lacked consistency or did not redirect them to the page they wanted to learn more from.</li>
            <li>All of the participants highlighted different aspects they wanted to learn more about on the Webinar and Services pages but lacked the expected structure on the desktop and mobile experiences to not be distracted by the unconventional layout.</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>User Stories</h4>
        <p>From the key research insights, I created user stories to prioritize for this website update:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>As a chronic pain sufferer who frequently uses their mobile phone, I want to comfortably read information easily on the services webpage using my mobile phone, so that I can decide if Psystem’s services are what I need for my chronic pain management journey.</li>
            <li>As a caretaker for a chronic pain sufferer, I want to quickly find information about Psystem’s webinars, so that I can register for upcoming informational sessions about how I can care for my loved one and myself. </li>
            <li>As a chronic pain sufferer who cannot sit for long sessions at a desk, I want to navigate the website from my tablet device, so that I can learn about Psystem’s free resources in a non-seated position.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="container cs-section">
        <h3>Ideate</h3>
        <p>Drawing inspiration from the competitor research and Psystem’s initial webpage layouts for the Webinar and Services pages, I sketched with pen and paper by applying the How Might We mindset to brainstorm and ideate various options to modify and optimize the Webinar and Services pages to provide more value to users while increasing user engagement.</p>
        <p>With the sketches, I selected the most impactful layouts to transfer into a digital low-fidelity format to share 3 variations with Psystem’s founder and project manager for a design review to get feedback and iterate before creating the high-fidelity mockups.</p>
        <img></img>
        <p>caption</p>
        <h4>Setting expectations: The Iterative Design Process and WCAG</h4>
        <p>In this phase, I took the opportunity to set expectations with the stakeholders about an iterative design process that would keep costs low when prioritizing low-fidelity wireframe iterations during the process of finalizing the layout and content for the webpages before moving forward with building the designs.</p>
        <p>During this conversation, I highlighted the importance of taking additional steps toward a more accessible website design by abiding by the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG).</p>
        <p>I proposed adjusting the hover states in the navigation menus, button sizes for tablet and mobile users, and typography for each screen size range to support a responsive website user experience.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="container cs-section">
        <h3>Iterate</h3>
        <p>From the initial feedback, I updated the wireframes as needed for a final review before moving forward with the high-fidelity mockups. This step was one of the next most exciting phases as I had the opportunity to learn more about Colour Vision Deficiency (CVD) as the founder shared insights about why certain colours are used in Psystem’s branding.</p>
        <h4>Creating Psystem’s Style Tile</h4>
        <p>I proposed adding a tertiary colour to highlight call-to-action sections and was grateful to test and review the idea with the founder to check that it adds value to their visual user experience while positively contributing to Psystem’s brand colours and supporting the landing page initiatives.</p>
        <p>To make my process more efficient, I summarized Psystem’s colours, typography, button styles, and interaction details into a style guide for future designers working with Psystem’s offerings and to maintain cohesive brand recognition for Psystem’s other offering, the PsyHealth mobile application.</p>
        <img></img>
        <p>caption</p>
    </div>
    <div class="container cs-section">
        <h3>Test</h3>
        <p>Since the pages were static landing pages, the testing phase was modified by using Webflow’s Staging Domain URL to gather feedback from internal testers about the high-fidelity mockups approved by the founder.</p>
        <p>Throughout the design process, I researched the implementation in Webflow’s Designer interface to ensure the feasibility of the ideas and suggestions I shared with Psystem’s founder.</p>
        <p>I reviewed the available features on Webflow to familiarize which aspects would be made from scratch or dragged and dropped from Webflow’s pre-made components.</p>
        <h4>“Testing” using Webflow’s Staging Domain</h4>
        <p>After translating all of the updates, I shared the staging domain URL with the founder and the internal user testers to conduct an informal usability study to learn about the following: </p>
        <ul>
            <li>How well users can navigate from page to page using the updated navigation menus in the global and footer sections,</li>
            <li>The users’ first impressions of how the content is organized help them learn more about Psystem’s services, and</li>
            <li>How easily users can find where and how to book a coaching appointment and subscribe to Psystem’s newsletter.</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>Discovering a minor yet impactful pain point</h4>
        <p>From testing using the Staging Domain, I gathered an additional insight about a “nice-to-have” feature to reduce endless scrolling that affects the users’ thumb mobility—the “Back to Top” button.</p>
        <p>I asked follow-up questions during this discussion to learn about the user’s expectations for where a “Back to Top” button would best support their experience in addition to learning more about how they interact with the interface as a right-handed dominant user.</p>
        <img></img>
        <p>caption</p>
        <img></img>
        <p>caption</p>
        <p>With my observations and a few proposed options, I got approval to test the “Back to Top” button on the Staging Domain by placing the button at the bottom left corner of the screen to avoid conflicting with the call-to-action booking button that is placed at the bottom right corner of the screen for the Services page.</p>
        <p>After another round of testing on the Staging Domain space, the goals for this project were met, the users were happy with having their needs met for the scope of this project, and the founder expressed their appreciation for how the pages were updated sooner than the anticipated timeline.</p>
    </div>
